data.content:
## ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

| Framework Pattern | Why It Breaks in Core |
|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | **Removed entirely.** It relied on `Thread.Abort()`, which doesn't exist in .NET Core. |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | The `endResponse` parameter is gone — no thread abort mechanism. |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Dead code — this exception no longer exists. |
| `Response.Clear()` / `AddHeader()` / `Write()` | Replaced by action return types and middleware pipeline. |
| `btnExport_Click` event handlers | Web Forms event model doesn't exist. Use controller actions + routing. |

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // POST /report/export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        // Return a FileResult — the framework handles Content-Disposition,
        // Content-Type, and flushing. No Response.End() needed.
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /report/process
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Process()
    {
        // Authentication is enforced declaratively, not with manual checks.
        // Unauthenticated users never reach this action.
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Returns 401 → middleware redirects to login (see config below)
            return Challenge();
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
            // Redirect() returns a 302 result object — it does NOT throw
            // or abort the thread. Code after this line would still execute
            // if you didn't return, which is a common migration pitfall.
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Failed to process report request");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch needed — it cannot happen.
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "col1,col2\nval1,val2";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Program.cs Configuration

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(CookieAuthenticationDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
    .AddCookie(options =>
    {
        // This replaces the manual Response.Redirect("/login") pattern
        options.LoginPath = "/login";
        options.AccessDeniedPath = "/error";
    });

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
app.MapControllerRoute(name: "default", pattern: "{controller}/{action}");
app.Run();
```

---

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `Redirect()` no longer stops execution**
```csharp
// WRONG — code after Redirect continues executing
Response.Redirect("/login");
DoSensitiveWork(); // THIS STILL RUNS!

// CORRECT — return the result immediately
return Redirect("/login");
```

**2. Don't manually write to `Response.Body` for file downloads**
```csharp
// WRONG — bypasses filters, error handling, content negotiation
Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
await Response.Body.WriteAsync(bytes);

// CORRECT — use the built-in result type
return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

**3. `Response.End()` has no equivalent — and you don't need one**

In Framework, `Response.End()` flushed the buffer and aborted the thread. In Core, returning an `IActionResult` signals the framework to write the response and complete the pipeline cleanly. There is nothing to "end."

**4. Swallowed `ThreadAbortException` blocks may hide real bugs**

Audit every `catch (ThreadAbortException)` in your codebase. Some mask logic errors that were silently ignored because the thread was killed. After migration, those code paths will execute fully — potentially causing double-redirects or data corruption.

**5. `HttpContext.Current` is gone**

If `GenerateReport()` or `ProcessRequest()` access `HttpContext.Current` (a static singleton), inject `IHttpContextAccessor` via DI instead — or better, pass the needed values explicitly.
